Essay Question: Based on steps 1.a, 1.b and 1.c, which variable RATIO or L_RATIO exhibits better conformance to a normal distribution with homogeneous variances across age classes? Why?

Answer: The L_Ratio variable does a better job at conforming to a normal distribution with homogeneous variance. The histogram in 1a for the ratio variable has a right skew with values trailing towards the positive side, which is also seen with the large upturn of the data points on the right of the Q-Q plot. In contrast, the L_Ratio variable has a fairly even amount of data points on either side of its histogram’s peak, which is corroborated by a close adherence to the straight line of the Q-Q plot. This is also seen with the bartlett tests, where the Ratio variable has a very small p-value with which we would reject the null hypothesis (at any of the 90%, 95% and even 99% confidence levels) that there are homogeneous variances. The L_Ratio’s bartlett test has a higher p-value of about .5, well within the bounds to accept the null hypothesis of homogeneous variances.

Harvest Strategy:

There is a tradeoff faced in managing abalone harvest. The infant population must be protected since it represents future harvests. On the other hand, the harvest should be designed to be efficient with a yield to justify the effort. This assignment will use VOLUME to form binary decision rules to guide harvesting. If VOLUME is below a “cutoff” (i.e. a specified volume), that individual will not be harvested. If above, it will be harvested. Different rules are possible.The Management needs to make a decision to implement 1 rule that meets the business goal.

The next steps in the assignment will require consideration of the proportions of infants and adults harvested at different cutoffs. For this, similar “for-loops” will be used to compute the harvest proportions. These loops must use the same values for the constants min.v and delta and use the same statement “for(k in 1:10000).” Otherwise, the resulting infant and adult proportions cannot be directly compared and plotted as requested. Note the example code supplied below.

More harvest strategies:

This part will address the determination of a cutoff volume.value corresponding to the observed maximum difference in harvest percentages of adults and infants. In other words, we want to find the volume value such that the vertical distance between the infant curve and the adult curve is maximum. To calculate this result, the vectors of proportions from item (6) must be used. These proportions must be converted from “not harvested” to “harvested” proportions by using (1 - prop.infants) for infants, and (1 - prop.adults) for adults. The reason the proportion for infants drops sooner than adults is that infants are maturing and becoming adults with larger volumes.

Note on ROC:

There are multiple packages that have been developed to create ROC curves. However, these packages - and the functions they define - expect to see predicted and observed classification vectors. Then, from those predictions, those functions calculate the true positive rates (TPR) and false positive rates (FPR) and other classification performance metrics. Worthwhile and you will certainly encounter them if you work in R on classification problems. However, in this case, we already have vectors with the TPRs and FPRs. Our adult harvest proportion vector, (1 - prop.adults), is our TPR. This is the proportion, at each possible ‘rule,’ at each hypothetical harvest threshold (i.e. element of volume.value), of individuals we will correctly identify as adults and harvest. Our FPR is the infant harvest proportion vector, (1 - prop.infants). We can think of TPR as the Confidence level (ie 1 - Probability of Type I error and FPR as the Probability of Type II error. At each possible harvest threshold, what is the proportion of infants we will mistakenly harvest? Our ROC curve, then, is created by plotting (1 - prop.adults) as a function of (1 - prop.infants). In short, how much more ‘right’ we can be (moving upward on the y-axis), if we’re willing to be increasingly wrong; i.e. harvest some proportion of infants (moving right on the x-axis)?

Essay Question: Based on the ROC curve, it is evident a wide range of possible “cutoffs” exist. Compare and discuss the five cutoffs determined in this assignment.

Answer: The cutoffs that preserve the largest amount of infants are the all infants cutoff and the median adult cutoff. If we choose to protect all the infants, we will have a very small harvest of adults (about 25% of adults and only 18% of the entire population). While we preserve the next generation of abalones, we also do not have a high volume of benefit from harvesting. In contrast, the median adults cutoff preserves most of the infants, only taking about 2.5%, while harvesting 50% of adults, for a total harvest of about 37%. If the goal is to prioritize infant preservation or abalone longevity, these options better accomplish that goal. How ever, the other three options have total harvest proportions of over 50%, so there is a much larger yield. Using the median infant volume harvests almost all of the adults and 82% of the total population, the largest harvest of the three cutoffs. If a 50% infant preservation rate is accepable for abalone longevity and sustainability, then this rate would achieve this goal with the highest profit (assuming higher harvest means higher profit). If a 50% infant cutoff is too high, the max volume difference and Max A1 Volume are better options. The Max A1 volume cutoff has a higher increase in the number of infants per adult, with only a 10% increase in harvest. The Max volume difference cutoff harvests just over a half of the total population, but still preserves over 75% of the infants.

Final Essay Question: Assume you are expected to make a presentation of your analysis to the investigators How would you do so? Consider the following in your answer:

  1. Would you make a specific recommendation or outline various choices and tradeoffs?
  2. What qualifications or limitations would you present regarding your analysis?
  3. If it is necessary to proceed based on the current analysis, what suggestions would you have for implementation of a cutoff?
  4. What suggestions would you have for planning future abalone studies of this type?

Answer: Assuming that both harvest volume and infant protection are important, I would recommend cutoffs of either the max volume difference or max a1 volume, which preserve about 72-83% of infants while still having a worthwhile harvest of 58-68%. The largest infant and median adult cutoffs do not seem to have very large harvest volumes, even if they preserve a lot of the infants. The median infant volume cutoff harvests half of the infants and almost all of the adults, which doesn’t leave much for a sustainable abalone population. If I had to choose one between the max volume difference and max a1 cutoffs, I would recommend the max volume difference. It preserve more infants (which implies better or sustained future harvests), while still having a relatively similar percentage of adults harvested. My qualifications for this recommendation is that I would choose the max volume difference or max a1 volume cutoff under the conditions that a 58-68% harvest is sufficient for profit, and that the 72-83% infant preservation is sufficient for abalone sustainability. The limitations of this approach is that if it is important to know the proportions of males and females being harvested, for purposes of abalone sustainability, the adult qualification does not make any differences between the two. For future abalone studies, I would recommend to collect more information than just the physical characteristics of the abalones. For example, diet or habitat could play a role in some of the volume differences, and could be strong predictive factors. Additionally, it might be helpful to either omit or (depending on how many there are) to create a third category for any uncertainties in characteristics like sex or class. If there were uncertainties, labeling them as equally truly belonging to that characteristic as any other certain member could have skewed some of the analyses and made relationships less discernible.
